• High changes rates may also be a sign of large numbers of software defects. 80% of software defects typically occur in 5% of the code, thus the strategy to “Renovate the Worst First” [Dav95] can pay off big by eliminating the most serious source of problems in the system. There are nevertheless considerable risks:
– it may be hard to demonstrate early, positive results, – you are tackling the most complicated part of the system with
little information, – the chances are higher that you will fall ﬂat on your face.
• Determine whether to wrap, refactor or rewrite the problematic component by making sure you Fix Problems, Not Symptoms.
Once you have decided what is the most valuable part of the system to work on, you should Involve the Users [p. 185] in the reengineering effort so you can Build Conﬁdence [p. 189]. If you Migrate Systems Incrementally [p. 191], the users will be able to use the system as it is reengineered and provide continuous feedback.

